04375nam a22007095i 9781501727160DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20182006nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017271607 a10.7591/97815017271602doi  a(DE-B1597)515070  a(OCoLC)1083626820  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHV4505b.F45 2004 7aSOC0450002bisacsh04a362.5/09732221 aFeldman, Leonard C., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCitizens without Shelter :bHomelessness, Democracy, and Political Exclusion /cLeonard C. Feldman. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (200 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION. State Power and the Polarities of Homeless Politics -- tCHAPTER 1. From Vagrancy Law to Contemporary Anti-homeless Policy -- tCHAPTER 2. The Legal Construction of the Homeless as Bare Life -- tCHAPTER 3. Redistribution, Recognition, and the Sovereign Ban -- tCHAPTER 4. Housing Diversity and Democratic Pluralism -- tCONCLUSION. The Empty Tent of Citizenship -- tNOTES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tCASES CITED -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOne of the most troubling aspects of the politics of homelessness, Leonard C. Feldman contends, is the reduction of the homeless to what Hannah Arendt calls "the abstract nakedness of humanity" and what Giorgio Agamben terms "bare life." Feldman argues that the politics of alleged compassion and the politics of those interested in ridding public spaces of the homeless are linked fundamentally in their assumption that homeless people are something less than citizens. Feldman's book brings political theories together (including theories of sovereign power, justice, and pluralism) with discussions of real-world struggles and close analyses of legal cases concerning the rights of the homeless.In Feldman's view, the "bare life predicament" is a product not simply of poverty or inequality but of an inability to commit to democratic pluralism. Challenging this reduction of the homeless, Citizens without Shelter examines opportunities for contesting such a fundamental political exclusion, in the service of homeless citizenship and a more robust form of democratic pluralism. Feldman has in mind a truly democratic pluralism that would include a pluralization of the category of "home" to enable multiple forms of dwelling; a recognition of the common dwelling activities of homeless and non-homeless persons; and a resistance to laws that punish or confine the homeless.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aHomeless personszUnited States. 0aHomelessnesszUnited States. 4aPhilosophy. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Poverty & Homelessness.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150172716040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501727160423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501727160/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK